<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0848-B"><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0025"><line>Some television networks here reported that the Istanbul court had already dropped charges against the novelist following the ministry statement, but there was no confirmation of those reports.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Justice Minister Cemil Cicek's decision came at a delicate time for European Union aspirant Turkey.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="47,51"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>But Monday's court decision will likely anger nationalists, including some within the government's conservative grass roots.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>&quot;I regret the decision... but it can't deflect me from the purpose of my visit,&quot; Straw said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Kemal Kerincsiz, a board member of the Turkish Lawyers' Union, said Monday that he would appeal the Pamuk decision.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>In each case, &quot;a satisfactory conclusion has been reached within an unsatisfactory situation.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>&quot;I hope therefore that the decision on Orhan Pamuk's case will pave the way for a positive outcome for them as well, so that freedom of expression for all Turkish citizens is fully respected.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0025"><line>As the country is considered for European Union membership, the trial is seen as a test of its commitment to freedom of expression.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>Rehn said he hoped the developments in Pamuk's case would help ease the plight of other writers and intellectuals being persecuted in Turkey.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>The next hearing is on Feb. 7.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>&quot;Pamuk is not the only case of a person prosecuted for having expressed a non-violent opinion in Turkey, it's just the most high-profile case,&quot; Rehn said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>There are shortcomings, and we're unified in eliminating them,&quot; on the road to the EU, Cicek said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>Pamuk was charged with insulting the country after telling a Swiss newspaper in February that &quot;30,000 Kurds and 1 million Armenians were killed in these lands, and nobody but me dares to talk about it.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>He urged the country's leaders to &quot;look much more seriously&quot; at a compromise proposal offered by Russian President Vladimir Putin.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>I hope therefore that the decision on Orhan Pamuk's case will pave the way for a positive outcome for them as well, so that freedom of expression for all Turkish citizens is fully respected.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>Pamuk, 53, risked six months to three years in jail for &quot;denigrating the Turkish national identity&quot; in remarks published in a Swiss magazine concerning the Armenian massacres of 1915-17.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>&quot;What we want to see is a situation where the laws that apply in Turkey... are the same as those which apply elsewhere in the European Union.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>The negotiations are expected to last at least a decade and the EU demands Turkey to carry out wide-ranging reforms.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Cicek's move was an apparent attempt to avoid upsetting both the EU and Turkish nationalists.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>Best-selling novelist Pamuk, 53, was charged with insulting the Turkish identity by saying that nobody in Turkey dared mention the killing of a million Armenians by the Ottoman Empire during World War I.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Turkey's justice minister has left a critical decision on whether to drop charges against novelist Orhan Pamuk to a local Istanbul court, according to officials, in an apparent attempt to avoid outraging Europe by allowing a renowned author to stand trial for his views or angering nationalists by dropping the case.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="5,8"><scu uid="5" label="Turkey's Justice Ministry sent Pamuk's case back to the Istanbul court." weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan's government has made joining the EU a cornerstone of its policy and passed sweeping reforms of Turkey's legal code.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>The trial had been set to resume on February 7.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>For Europeans who oppose Turkey's membership in their club of democracies, the prosecution of Pamuk reinforced the view that the nation of 70 million Muslims, while a useful buffer between Europe and the Middle East, is no part of contemporary European civilization.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>But Straw also said in an interview with The Associated Press that he hoped the International Atomic Energy Agency, the U.N. nuclear watchdog, would decide during its Feb. 2-3 emergency meeting to refer the nuclear standoff to the U.N. Security Council.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line><line>Straw also praised a Turkish court's decision Monday to drop charges of &quot;insulting Turkishness&quot; against international acclaimed novelist Orhan Pamuk, but said the country still needs to boost human rights as it works toward hoped-for membership in the European Union.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="13,29,3,35,36,55"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>&quot;This case should not have been opened in the first place.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>The next hearing is scheduled for Feb. 7.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>Pamuk was facing a sentence of up to three years in jail if he was convicted of insulting the Turkish identity in the interview he gave to Das Magazine, a Swiss publication, in 2005.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>&quot;We've got good relations with the government of Russia,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>The Pamuk case became the focus of critics against the 25-nation bloc opening entry talks with Turkey last October.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>The case has attracted huge international attention and cast a pall on Turkey's commitment to free speech at a time when the EU is closely monitoring the membership candidate's adherence to democratic values.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>&quot;The court dropped the charges not because the trial violated the freedom of speech,&quot; he said, but because &quot;there was a missing approval by the Justice Ministry to proceed with the trial.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>The country's press organizations have accused the government of lacking the political will to change laws hindering free expression.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="2" label="Turkish intellectuals demanded that Turkey change the laws limiting freedom of expression." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>Rehn said the current judicial laws &quot;leave too much room for abusive and restrictive interpretations limiting freedom of expression.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>&quot;At each stage up to now there's been a high level of speculation in advance of meetings of the IAEA,&quot; Straw said as he flew from London to Cyprus on a three-day trip including scheduled stops in Greece and Turkey.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>&quot;Orhan Pamuk must be punished for insulting Turkey and Turkishness, it is a grave crime and it should not be left unpunished.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line><line>In the opening hearing of the trial Dec. 16, a judge threw the case back to the Justice Ministry, demanding that the government first approve it.</line><line>Writers' advocacy group International PEN welcomed the dropping of charges but said it was not nearly enough.</line><line>A Turkish court dropped charges of &quot;insulting Turkishness&quot; Monday against internationally acclaimed novelist Orhan Pamuk, ending a trial that outraged even the most passionate advocates of Turkey's EU membership bid by raising questions about the nation's commitment to freedom of speech.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="22,23,29,3,35,49,55"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>The author of critically acclaimed books including &quot;My Name is Red,&quot; &quot;Snow&quot; and &quot;Istanbul,&quot; had faced up to three years in prison for telling a Swiss newspaper in February: &quot;Thirty-thousand Kurds and 1 million Armenians were killed in these lands, and nobody but me dares to talk about it.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>Pamuk's high profile abroad, in Europe and elsewhere, prompted widespread opposition to his prosecution, an advantage that many intellectuals who face similar charges do not have, said Vecdi Sayar, general secretary of International PEN, a worldwide association of writers.</line><line>Pamuk, whose works have been translated into dozens of languages, spoke in a newspaper interview about the mass killings of Armenians by the Ottoman Empire in 1915, and also of the deaths of Kurds in Turkish operations in the 1980s against a separatist group.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>The trial of Pamuk, Turkey's most famous writer, which began last month, had been adjourned pending a decision by the justice ministry, whose authorization was needed to continue the case.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="33,40"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>&quot;Several journalists, editors, writers and academics still face similar charges today,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Pamuk's trial had outraged even those favoring Turkey's membership bid by raising questions about its commitment to freedom of speech.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="35"><scu uid="3" label="The EU demanded that Turkey change the laws limiting freedom of expression." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>But Justice Minister Cemil Cicek on Friday admitted shortcomings in Turkey's judicial system and promised more legal reforms.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>The court had adjourned Pamuk's trial shortly after it began on Dec. 16 and asked the Justice Ministry for a legal opinion on whether he could be tried under a new penal code.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>The ruling was immediately welcomed by the European legislators.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>Pamuk had been charged with insulting the Turkish nation in remarks on the mass killings of Armenians during World War One.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="13,37"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Straw said Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan had already made impressive changes, but that the reality of the rights situation didn't always keep up with his legislative reforms.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Turkey is still not off the hook, however, as dozens of people are still facing charges similar to Pamuk's.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="13" label="Other intellectuals have been charged, but do not have as high a profile as Pamuk." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>Pamuk's lawyer has confirmed the dismissal of the case.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Pamuk's remarks referred to two of the most painful episodes in recent Turkish history: The massacre of Armenians during World War I, which Turkey insists was not a planned genocide, and recent guerrilla fighting in Turkey's overwhelmingly Kurdish southeast.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="49"><scu uid="18" label="Pamuk talked about Kurdish deaths." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>A group of Turkish writers, academics, journalists and artists called on the government Monday to scrap laws that limit freedom of expression, including one under which the country's most famous novelist has been charged.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="14,44,51"><scu uid="2" label="Turkish intellectuals demanded that Turkey change the laws limiting freedom of expression." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>PEN says that about 70 intellectuals have been charged under Article 301 of the revised penal code, which calls for punishment for public comments that &quot;denigrate Turkishness, the government, the army and the memory of the founder of modern Turkey, Mustafa Kemal Ataturk.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0025"><line>Turkey has come under heavy criticism from international human rights groups and governments.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>But each of these negotiations has gone to the wire.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>The subject of the 1915 massacres remains taboo in Turkey.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>&quot;What I'm very anxious to ensure is that we don't see movement backwards,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>The case also divided Turkey and embarrassed the nation's liberals.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>Pamuk, Turkey's best-selling writer, is the author of internationally renowned works such as &quot;My Name is Red&quot; and &quot;Snow&quot; and winner of a number of literary awards.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Putin has offered to allow uranium enrichment for Iran to be conducted in Russia where it could be supervised.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0025"><line>The Justice Ministry on Sunday cited amendments made to the penal code last year in saying that the court should determine whether to proceed, the semiofficial Anatolian news agency reported.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Such a decision could still outrage nationalists who pelted Pamuk's car with eggs, shouting &quot;Traitor!&quot; and &quot;Love it or leave it!&quot; in reference to Turkey during the opening hearing on Dec. 16.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>The case against Pamuk, praised by Turkish nationalists, drew condemnations from the European Union, which warned it was a test of freedom of speech in Turkey.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="3" label="The EU demanded that Turkey change the laws limiting freedom of expression." weight="3"/><scu uid="26" label="Turkish nationalists were outraged." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>The West fears Iran wants to develop a nuclear bomb, but Tehran says its intentions are peaceful and that it is only seeking to develop the capacity for civilian nuclear energy.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>The government apparently did not want to risk a face off with the EU over the sensitive case.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Cyprus' president has refused to see Straw to protest the foreign secretary's planned meeting with the Turkish Cypriot leader, Mehmet Ali Talat, on Wednesday.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>It was not clear when the court would issue its decision.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>Pamuk, who has won several international literary prizes, risked up to three years in prison for remarks made during an interview published in a Swiss magazine last February.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>This week, the EU is to begin a review of the country's justice system.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>&quot;One million Armenians and 30,000 Kurds were killed in these lands and nobody but me dares talk about it,&quot; Pamuk told Das Magazin in February.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Coming just days before the EU is to begin a review of Turkey's much criticized justice system, the court decision was a sign that the long-desired goal of joining the wealthy EU was slowly forcing the government to embrace European norms of freedom and democracy.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="10,29"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>Turkey categorically denies Armenian accusations that up to 1.5 million of their kinsmen died in a genocide orchestrated by the Ottoman Empire between 1915 and 1917.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>The group, which includes novelist Yasar Kemal and pianist Fazil Say, said the government should do away with the law that makes it a crime to insult the Turkish republic, &quot;Turkishness&quot; or state institutions, which was used against Pamuk.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>&quot;Article 301 and others curbing freedom of expression which do not fit Turkey's democratic image must be changed,&quot; said Inanici.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>He hopes to learn whether the two sides are open to refocusing on U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's settlement plan for the war-torn island, which was approved by Turkish Cypriots but rejected by Greek Cypriots in separate referendums in 2004, only days before the island joined the European Union.</line><line>Britain, France and Germany declared after Iran's decision that their two years of talks with Tehran had reached a dead end, and they are pressing along with the United States for the issue to be referred to the U.N. Security Council which has the power to impose sanctions.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>&quot;It is a scandal,&quot; Kerincsiz said by telephone.</line><line>European officials have repeatedly asked that Turkey change its laws to take the legal ammunition away from those who would prosecute speech offenses in Turkey.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>Pamuk went on trial for telling a Swiss newspaper in February that Turkey is unwilling to deal with two of the most painful episodes in recent Turkish history: the massacre of Armenians during World War I, which Turkey insists was not a planned genocide, and recent guerrilla fighting in Turkey's overwhelmingly Kurdish southeast.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="49"><scu uid="18" label="Pamuk talked about Kurdish deaths." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>I'm glad they decided apparently... not to pursue it,&quot; Straw said.</line><line>&quot;Relations will continue.&quot;</line><line>British Foreign Secretary Jack Straw urged Tehran on Tuesday to seriously consider Russia's offer to enrich Iran's uranium in an effort to end its nuclear standoff with countries that want to refer it to the U.N. Security Council.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,51"/></line><line>So I hope that that's where we'll get to....</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>Pamuk's lawyer could not be reached to confirm the television report.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="47"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>He declined to comment on allegations by Russia's intelligence agency that four British diplomats in Moscow were involved in espionage, or to say how the charges might affect ties between London and Moscow.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>Turkey has rejected allegations of genocide against Armenians during World War I.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>&quot;Saving a writer like Orhan Pamuk from prosecution may stand as a symbolic example on its own.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>During the trial nationalists pelted Pamuk's car with eggs, shouting &quot;Traitor!&quot; and &quot;Love it or leave it!&quot; in reference to Turkey.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Pamuk was charged under a law that makes insulting Turkey a crime after a Swiss newspaper in February quoted him as saying: &quot;30,000 Kurds and 1 million Armenians were killed in these lands, and nobody but me dares to talk about it.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>&quot;They've still got quite a long way to go, and they know, they don't need me to tell them that decisions like the one to arrest the novelist Orhan Pamuk don't help.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="18,8"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Then last week, Cicek sent the case back to the local court, saying the ministry has no say under a new penal code.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="44"><scu uid="5" label="Turkey's Justice Ministry sent Pamuk's case back to the Istanbul court." weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;It does little to assuage PEN's concerns that the right to freedom of expression in Turkey is severely curtailed by the existence of laws that penalize debate on &quot;taboo&quot; topics,&quot; PEN said in a written statement.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>On Sunday, the Justice Ministry told the court to make the decision, citing changes made to the penal code last year.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>The case has catched international limelight and the European Union has voiced grave concerns over it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0025"><line>The Justice Ministry's action sent the case back to an Istanbul court, which in December had postponed the trial, saying that it was up to the government to decide whether to proceed with the case.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Pamuk, author of &quot;Snow&quot; and &quot;My Name is Red&quot; and an often-mentioned candidate for the Nobel prize in literature, said in a brief statement to the press after the trial that &quot;it is not good for Turkey, for our democracy, for such freedom of expression cases to be prolonged.&quot;</line><line>The local court could now drop the charges against Pamuk, based on a technicality, saying the Justice Ministry's consent is missing from the file.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="38,8"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>&quot;The court dropped the case,&quot; Haluk Inanici, the author's lawyer, told the AP by telephone.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Iran's top nuclear negotiator, Ali Larijani, was meeting Tuesday with Russian officials in Moscow, a day after Tehran warned that a referral to the U.N. Security Council would lead it to immediately forge ahead with a full-scale uranium enrichment program.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>EU enlargement chief Olli Rehn hailed Monday a Turkish decision to drop charges against prominent author Orhan Pamuk, but pressed Ankara over similar cases and urged the country to review its law.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="7" sums="19,25,32,42,44,5,57"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/><scu uid="7" label="The EU welcomed the ruling." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>&quot;The authority in this issue belongs to (the justice system),&quot; the state-owned Anatolia news agency on Sunday quoted Cicek as telling the court in his written response.</line><line>The nation has carried out a sweeping series of reforms to expand freedom of expression as part of its EU membership drive, but nationalist prosecutors and judges often still interpret laws in a restrictive manner.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>&quot;Several journalists, editors, writers and academics still face similar charges today.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>The local court had argued that it cannot continue the trial since there was no approval from the justice ministry to try Pamuk for his remarks which predate the June reform.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Olli Rehn, EU enlargement commissioner said in a statement that the decision to dismiss charges was &quot;good news for freedom of expression in Turkey&quot; but warned that Turkey &quot;needs to fill properly the loopholes&quot; in its penal code, which he said limit freedom of expression.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="20,21,43"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>And he warned: &quot;It is clear for me that Turkey needs to fill properly the loopholes of the current Penal Code, which leave too much room for abusive and restrictive interpretations limiting freedom of expression.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>Olli Rehn, the EU commissioner in charge of expansion, said the decision to drop the case against Pamuk was &quot;good news for freedom of expression in Turkey,&quot; but said Turkey &quot;needs to fill properly the loopholes&quot; in its penal code.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="18,20,43"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>The nationalist lawyers behind the charges have vowed to continue prosecuting those who allegedly break the law by insulting Turkey.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="38"><scu uid="13" label="Other intellectuals have been charged, but do not have as high a profile as Pamuk." weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>The remark was taken as an insult to Turkey, and a prosecutor opened a case against the oft-mentioned candidate for the Nobel Prize under article 301 of the new penal code, which sets penalties for insults against the Turkish Republic or &quot;Turkishness.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>An Istanbul court has dropped charges against prominent author Orhan Pamuk, who was accused of &quot;denigrating the Turkish national identity&quot; over remarks he made about the mass killings of Armenians during World War I, CNN-Turk television reported Sunday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="6" sums="11,16,33,40,41,6"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>However the lawyer for the novelist, Haluk Inanici, chided the court for framing its decision in bureaucratic terms rather than addressing the issue of freedom of expression.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="30" label="The court was criticized for framing the dismissal in bureaucratic terms." weight="2"/><scu uid="32" label="The court was criticized for not addressing freedom of expression." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>On Monday, the Istanbul court said: &quot;It was necessary to decide to drop the case because there was no explicit authorization for prosecution.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Straw is trying to build new support for a stalled Cyprus peace plan in a visit to the divided island.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>A Turkish court has dropped charges against renowned novelist Orhan Pamuk for insulting the Turkish identity, local newspaper HURRIYET (Freedom) reported on Monday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="9" sums="20,21,22,23,37,43,44,55,57"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>&quot;There are many people abroad who fail to see beyond Orhan Pamuk's trial,&quot; Sayar said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>Pamuk's remarks highlighted two of the most painful episodes in Turkish history: the massacre of Armenians during World War I _ which Turkey insists was not a planned genocide _ and recent guerrilla fighting in Turkey's overwhelmingly Kurdish southeast.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Straw said Tuesday that talks about Iran would continue right up to the IAEA decision.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="51"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>EU officials have harshly criticized such laws and a group of 169 intellectuals issued a statement, saying they viewed Orhan Pamuk's trial as &quot;a grave interference in our country's democratization process.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>An Istanbul court dropped charges against the novelist Orhan Pamuk on Monday, ending a trial that put Turkey at odds with the European Union over the issue of freedom of speech.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="6" sums="12,13,16,22,25,55"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/><scu uid="3" label="The EU demanded that Turkey change the laws limiting freedom of expression." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051226.0357"><line>Earlier this month, a group of observers from the European Parliament attending Pamuk's trial demanded that Turkey change the article used against Pamuk or risk putting its EU bid in jeopardy.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="47"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>He said he wasn't expecting major progress any time soon.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>On Monday the court dropped the charges.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="13,32,6"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Cicek, however, reiterated to the court that his ministry has no say in the matter under the new penal code passed in June, a senior Justice Ministry official said, speaking on condition of anonymity because he was not authorized to speak to the media.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="23" label="The Justice Ministry  refused to issue an approval of the prosecution" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>&quot;Pamuk is not the only case of a person prosecuted for having expressed a non-violent opinion in Turkey, it's just the most high-profile case,&quot; Rehn said.</line><line>&quot;Turkey is a state of law.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>In its progress report on Turkey last year, the European Commission also called on Ankara to ensure its penal code reforms were implemented to ensure democratic freedoms were protected in its court system.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>The EU started talks with Ankara on its entry bid in October.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>He was then prosecuted for &quot;insulting Turkish identity.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0361"><line>The European Union welcomed a Turkish court decision Monday to drop charges against well-known novelist Orhan Pamuk, but warned Ankara that it must address legal loopholes that limit freedom of speech in other cases.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="12" sums="10,11,12,14,23,25,29,36,37,41,55,6"><scu uid="6" label="The Istanbul court dropped the charges against Pamuk." weight="4"/><scu uid="3" label="The EU demanded that Turkey change the laws limiting freedom of expression." weight="3"/><scu uid="7" label="The EU welcomed the ruling." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0025"><line>The Turkish Justice Ministry on Sunday declined to rule on whether a criminal trial of the novelist Orhan Pamuk on a charge of insulting &quot;Turkishness&quot; should proceed.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="11,14,16,19,33,41,43,48"><scu uid="5" label="Turkey's Justice Ministry sent Pamuk's case back to the Istanbul court." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>But it is not an overall resolution for other intellectuals and writers that still face similar charges in Turkey.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Cicek's response was sent to the court on Friday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>Turkey categorically denies Armenian accusations that up to 1.5 million of their kinsmen died in a genocide orchestrated by the Ottoman Empire in the last years of its existence.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Cicek insisted that the amendments in the penal code in June has lifted the ministry's say over the case.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060123.0267"><line>&quot;This is obviously good news for Mr Pamuk, but it's also good news for freedom of expression in Turkey,&quot; Rehn said in a statement.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>I don't think this one will be any different,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>&quot;One million Armenians and 30,000 Kurds were killed in these lands and nobody but me dares talk about it,&quot; he told Das Magazin in February.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0868"><line>Earlier this month, Foreign Minister Abdullah Gul acknowledged that charges brought against Pamuk had tarnished the country's image and said for the first time that laws that limit freedom of expression may be changed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>On Oct. 3, Turkey realized one of its dreams when the EU agreed to open membership talks with the overwhelmingly Muslim country.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>CNN-Turk said the ministry had declared in a letter to the tribunal that it was legally not competent to judge whether the case should go on, and the court had thus decided to dismiss the case.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Straw said the European allies were open to resuming talks with Iran, if it suspends uranium enrichment activities.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20060123.0113"><line>The Istanbul court's decision came after the Justice Ministry said that the court had no authority to try him.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="43,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>Turkey has for years come under severe EU criticism for laws that stifle freedom of speech.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>Some EU lawmakers who attended the December hearing said the trial could affect the country's aspirations to join the bloc.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060124.1046"><line>Dozens of people still face similar charges, though, and the EU is about to begin a review of Turkey's much-criticized justice system.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="3"><scu uid="13" label="Other intellectuals have been charged, but do not have as high a profile as Pamuk." weight="2"/><scu uid="8" label="The decision was made just before the EU was to review Turkey's justice system." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>The local court _ which halted the trial of Pamuk on Dec. 16, the day it began _ had asked the ministry whether it should continue with the case.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060122.0403"><line>When contacted by AFP, a justice minitry official declined any immediate comment on news of the court's decision but said the ministry would address the issue on Monday.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060123.0032"><line>The high-profile trial has already outraged European Union officials and sparked questions over the country's commitment to free speech.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060123.0156"><line>The court had asked the government to rule on whether to proceed with the case.</line></document></collection>